SIMPLE: origin
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Origin
<hw>Or"i*gin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>origine</ets>, L. <ets>origo</ets>, <ets>-iginis</ets>, fr.
<ets>oriri</ets> to rise, become visible; akin to Gr.
<grk>'orny`nai</grk> to stir up, rouse, Skr. <ets>⟦rsdot⟧</ets>, and
perh. to E. <ets>run</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The first existence or beginning of anything; the
birth.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This mixed system of opinion and sentiment had its
<qex>origin</qex> in the ancient chivalry.</q>
<rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That from which anything primarily proceeds; the
fountain; the spring; the cause; the occasion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The point of attachment or end of
a muscle which is fixed during contraction; -- in contradistinction to
<contr>insertion</contr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Origin of coordinate axes</b></col> <fld>(Math.)</fld>,
<cd>the point where the axes intersect. See Note under
<er>Ordinate</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Commencement; rise; source; spring; fountain;
derivation; cause; root; foundation.</syn> <usage> -- <er>Origin</er>,
<er>Source</er>. <xex>Origin</xex> denotes the rise or commencement of a
thing; <xex>source</xex> presents itself under the image of a fountain
flowing forth in a continuous stream of influences. The
<xex>origin</xex> of moral evil has been much disputed, but no one can
doubt that it is the <xex>source</xex> of most of the calamities of our
race.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I think he would have set out just as he did, with the
<qex>origin</qex> of ideas -- the proper starting point of a grammarian,
who is to treat of their signs.</q> <rj><qau>Tooke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Famous Greece,⟦br⟧
That <qex>source</qex> of art and cultivated thought⟦br⟧
Which they to Rome, and Romans hither, brought.</q>
<rj><qau>Waller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Originable</ent>⟦br⟧
